fields.value: Germantown in the 20th century saw decline as its industries became less dominant and moved towards closure. Growth was still occurring at the beginning of the century, marked by rowhouses and denser housing replacing the historic large mansions in the area, primarily to the east of Germantown Avenue near industries. Such crowded and polluted conditions would contribute to the neighborhood's decline. By the 1940s, the neighborhood start to see an influx of African Americans attracted to industrial and service jobs in the area, the third highest rate of racial change in the city. Such dramatic demographic change in an area formerly dominated by German-, English-, and Italian-Americans causes racial tensions and depopulation of these groups. Urban Renewal efforts in the 50s and 60s effectively cut off the neighborhood from the rest of the city through the construction of the Roosevelt Expressway. By the 70s Germantown Avenue is designated as a historic district, an attempt by the dominant hegemony to maintain its historical roots in the neighborhood. Such conditions - aging and frozen condition of housing stock, racial tensions, a cut-off and  impoverished population - set the stage for Germantown in the 21st century.
